benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: POST /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/block - Block a bundle

covered: Valid Payload scenarios (TC01-TC04) demonstrate successful creation with required and optional inputs and headers.
Large payload handling (TC16) tests maximum field sizes in BlockingState.
Input validation and error scenarios (TC06, TC08, TC09, TC10, TC11, TC12) cover invalid bundleId, malformed body, missing headers/body, invalid dates, and unexpected params.
Authorization and authentication scenarios (TC18, TC09) test token validity and header requirements.
Availability and resilience scenarios (TC17, TC21, TC28) test service downtime, network interruptions, and dependency failures with appropriate error codes.
Performance/load scenarios (TC25, TC26) check response times under normal and peak loads.
Concurrency and regression coverage (TC22, TC23, TC24) test concurrent requests and compatibility with special characters and prior clients.
Integration/data consistency (TC29) ensures blocking state consistency across systems.
gaps: Duplicate submission/idempotency handling is not covered.
Rate limiting/throttling scenarios are not covered.
Caching behavior (ETag/Cache-Control) for POST not covered.
Explicit 500 Internal Server Error simulations (DB failure) are not present.
Expanded authorization coverage (expired tokens/permissions) could be included.
Further integration tests to validate cross-system data consistency under various failure/recovery scenarios could be added.
recommendations: Add a dedicated idempotency/duplicate submission test to ensure repeated requests are handled gracefully.
Add rate-limiting tests to verify throttling behavior under high request volume.
Add tests for caching headers or verify no undesired caching for POST responses.
Introduce tests that simulate DB/internal server failures resulting in 500 errors to validate proper server error handling.
Expand authorization tests to cover expired tokens and insufficient permissions.
Augment integration tests to verify data consistency across dependent services during failure and recovery.
